&gt; I am not able to understand how join is working.

It&#39;s really simple. `t.join()` does _nothing._ It keeps doing nothing until the thread `t` is finished, and then it returns. That&#39;s all there is to it.

You could also think of `t.join()` as being like `Thread.sleep(n)` except that, instead of sleeping until `n` milliseconds have elapsed, it sleeps until thread `t` is finished.

----------------

P.S., You wrote this:

``` lang-java
Thread t2 = Thread.currentThread();
try{
    t2.join();
}
catch(InterruptedException e){
    System.out.println(e);
}
```

That&#39;s going to sleep forever. `Thread.currentThread()` has a misleading name. It should be called something like `Thread.caller()` or `Thread.self()` or `Thread.me()`. It returns the `Thread` instance of the thread that called it.

When you wrote `t2.join()` you are saying, wait until `t2` is finished, but `t2` is the thread that&#39;s calling `t2.join()`. The `join()` call won&#39;t return until the thread is finished, but the thread cannot finish until the `join()` call returns. Some people call that a _self deadlock._

